We reiterated our recommendation that Management:

Require the concerned Accountable Officer to submit the accounts and financial reports to the Municipal Treasurer pursuant to the timelines of the abovementioned existing law, rules and regulations; 

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit to the Municipal Accounting Office all the disbursements vouchers, payrolls, official receipts, including the corresponding reports for each month on or before the fifth day of the ensuing month or pursuant to the abovementioned pertinent provisions of rules and regulations, as applicable; 

Direct the Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the timelines on the recording and submission of accounts to the Auditor within ten days of the ensuing month; and

Identify and address the cause/s for the poor performance in the submission of monthly financial reports/accounts.

Submit the following documents:
Authority such as Office Orders or Memoranda, indicating the names of persons who were assigned to COVID-19 facilities directly catering to or in contact with COVID-19 patients and the period of their assignment;
Duly accomplished and approved daily time record;
Detailed computation of claim amounting to P1.44 million indicating therein the number of days physically reported for work during the month, COVID-19 patient attended to and quarantine period of patients; and
Duly verified accomplishment/monitoring reports of employees for the period December 20, 2020 to June 30, 2021
Require the refund of SRA from personnel who are not entitled thereof being not in direct contact or did not cater to COVID-19 patients;
Strictly adhere to the provisions of RA No. 11469 of the “Bayanihan to Heal as One Act” and subsequent issuances relative thereof to address the needs on the national emergency arising from the COVID-19 pandemic; and
Support all transactions with valid, complete and proper documents as required under Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 2012-001.

We reiterate our prior year’s recommendation that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) require:
The Property Officer to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete LRNPCs for all roads and its components;
The Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and reconcile the same with the LRNPCs and the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of each year;
The Municipal Accountant to ensure that only depreciable road components are subjected to depreciation and prepare the adjusting entry for the recorded depreciation expenses on road lots; and
The Municipal Accountant to include the necessary disclosure on the total road network system of the LGU in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that Management:
Require the concerned Accountable Officer to submit the accounts and financial reports to the Municipal Treasurer pursuant to the timelines of the abovementioned existing law, rules and regulations;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit to the Municipal Accounting Office all the disbursements vouchers, payrolls, official receipts, including the corresponding reports for each month on or before the fifth day of the ensuing month or pursuant to the abovementioned pertinent provisions of rules and regulations, as applicable;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with the timelines on the recording and submission of accounts to the Auditor within ten days of the ensuing month; and
Identify and address the cause/s for the poor performance in the submission of monthly financial reports/accounts.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendation that Management:
Send demand letter to concerned officials and employees with unliquidated cash advances requesting immediate settlement thereof;
In case of failure to settle the cash advance after two demand letters, withhold the payment of salaries of the concerned accountable officer to enforce settlement thereof;
Before processing a claim for cash advance, the Municipal Accountant shall ensure that the previous cash advance of the concerned official or employee has been settled;
The Municipal Accountant shall strictly monitor that all cash advances granted are liquidated within the required period of settlement;
Submit a copy of the demand letter issued to the ICO-Municipal Treasurer together with pertinent documents to prove its settlement, if any; and
Require the ICO-Municipal Treasurer to immediately settle all unliquidated cash advances. She shall maintain a record of all cash advances received and liquidated to serve as a ready reference in determining the unliquidated balance per cash advance received so as to prevent the accumulation of long outstanding cash advances.

We recommended that Management make the necessary confirmation with concerned agencies whose names still appear in the listing of outstanding funds which remained in the books of the Municipality to ascertain the action to be taken onwards, viz:
Return to the concerned source agencies the unutilized balance of the fund transfer wherein the agreement requires the return thereof;
Revert to Government Equity the balances of fund transfers in the nature of financial assistance and subsidy wherein the agreement does not mention of the disposition of the unused balance and that future utilization thereof will be subject to the usual accounting, auditing and budgeting laws, rules and regulations;
Retain special purpose funds; and
Clean the books of accounts, particularly the accounts Due to LGUs and Due to NGAs, in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2016-005 in order to present fairly the Liability accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE) institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities:
to conduct risk assessment;
to identify critical processes and functions;
to determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation;
to conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
to formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
to submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP.
Further, we recommended that members of the working group be capacitated by allowing them to attend seminars/trainings on the formulation of the PSCP.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management:
Present regular/flagship programs/projects of the LGU under the section, Attributed Programs of the GAD Plan and Budget and the GAD Accomplishment Report;
Employ the HGDG tool for regular/flagship programs/projects of the LGU and identify which part of the project cost/expenditure is attributable to the GAD Budget;
Maximize the utilization of the GAD funds through the identification and implementation of GAD-related programs and projects in order to attain the objectives for which funds were provided;
Strictly observe the timelines in the submission of GPB and GAD AR to the Audit Team; and
Capacitate the GFPS by allowing them to attend trainings and seminars especially on the use of the HGDG tool.

